Signal Processing: Spectrogram Analysis and Filtering

Concepts used: Fourier Transform, Frequency Spectrum, Filtering
Software used: MATLAB

This project concerns signal processing of a time domain signal to identify frequency content of the signal and manipulate the signal to isolate its specific features. The spectrogram was self-made instead of using the built-in MATLAB function in order to better understand its innerworkings. The whole code for this project is provided later in the page.

The signal to be analyzed is a bird whistle shown below.

Using the self-made spectrogram, the frequency content of the above signal is shown below

From the above spectrogram, the frequency range at which the dominant bird chirp is identified in the area shown (1700 to 2600 Hz). This is confirmed in the video below, where the dominant bird chirp corresponds very well to these "spots" inside the identified range.

The signal is then filtered to isolate these frequencies. A FIR filter is used since the situation is an offline computation, therefore the higher accuracy of FIR over IIR can be exploited. The result is shown below:

From the frequency response above it is seen that there is still a significant contribution of frequencies outside the bandpass. In addition, it was found that there is a phase shift in the filtered signal, causing the filtered bird chirp to be delayed compared to the original. To remedy these problems, a zero-phase filter with a reflection method is applied to remove phase shift as well as edge effects. The result is more attenuation of frequency content outside of the bandpass, and notably better attenuation just outside the transition region. This therefore indicates the design method followed successfully improves the raw filtered signal. The final frequency response is shown below:

And the final filtered signal can be listened below:

The following shows the code used in this project.

Spectrogram and FIR filtering of a Bird Whistle

Spectrogram and FIR filtering of a Bird Whistle

1. Read and pre-process data

clear
warning off
%Read time domain signal
[ori_signal2,fs] = audioread('XC403881.mp3');
%Take only first channel of this particular signal
ori_signal=ori_signal2(:,1);
%Length of signal
n = length(ori_signal);
timevec = (0:n-1)/fs;
%Check time signal and make sure it makes sense
figure
plot(timevec,ori_signal);
xlabel('Time (s)')
ylabel('Amplitude')
title('Time Signal')
xlim([0 10])
%Optional; listen to the audio
%sound(ori_signal2,fs)

2. Frequency Spectrum

%First create the frequency bins.
frequency_bins_freqresp=linspace(0,fs/2,floor(n/2)+1);
%Next remove DC component of signal so that the frequency response is not
%dominated by this component
ori_signal=ori_signal-mean(ori_signal);
%Now find the FFT and compute power
ori_signal_freqresp=abs(fft(ori_signal)/n).^2;
%Truncate the power vector to only include the ones up to Nyquist frequency
ori_signal_freqresp=ori_signal_freqresp(1:length(frequency_bins_freqresp));
%Plot
figure
plot(frequency_bins_freqresp,ori_signal_freqresp);hold on
xlim([0 8000]);
xline(1700);xline(2600);hold off
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)');
ylabel('Power Density');
title('Frequency spectrum');

3. Setup data for spectrogram

%Choose length of window; smaller windows mean more "slices" and so we get
%more information about which frequencies are dominant over smaller time
%intervals. However, smaller windows also mean low frequencies do not fit
%into the window and so any dominant low frequencies are not going to be
%accurately represented in the window (i.e. lowered frequency resolution)
windowLengthInDatapoints=2500;
noverlap=windowLengthInDatapoints/2; % For 50% overlap
%Find start points of each window
start_points=linspace(1,length(timevec),windowLengthInDatapoints-noverlap);
%Remove startpoints whose corresponding window length will overshoot the end of the
%time series
start_points=start_points(start_points + windowLengthInDatapoints < length(timevec));
%Set frequency bins
frequency_bins=linspace(0,fs/2,floor(windowLengthInDatapoints/2)+1);

4. Compute spectrogram

%Compute power spectrum of each window
for wi=1:length(start_points)
window_signal=ori_signal(start_points(wi):start_points(wi)+windowLengthInDatapoints);
%To reduce spectral leakage, multiply each window with a Hann window
%This makes the true frequency peaks clearer
hann_window=hann(length(window_signal));
window_signal=window_signal.*hann_window;
window_signal_fft_all=abs(fft(window_signal)/windowLengthInDatapoints).^2;
window_signal_fft(wi,:)=window_signal_fft_all(1:length(frequency_bins));
end

5. Plot spectrogram

figure
%Plot the magnitude in dB; in sound processing dB is defined as 10*log10
%instead of 20*log10 in other domains
Pref = 2*10^-5;
imagesc(timevec,frequency_bins,10*log10(window_signal_fft'./Pref^2));
colormap(jet(128))
set(gca,'YDir','normal')
set(gca,'ylim',[0 15000])
xlabel('Time (s)')
ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
h=colorbar;
ylabel(h,'Magnitude (dB)')
title('spectrogram of Bird Chirp')
yline(1700,'linewidth',2);yline(2600,'linewidth',2);
From the spectrogram it's clear that the dominant chirps we heard are in the range shown inside the vertical lines. We can isolate this sound to hear it better by applying a filter.

6. Now apply FIR filter to isolate bird chirps

Here we design the FIR filter; FIR is used because the signal is processed offline and so the higher accuracy of FIR over IIR can be obtained. The filter order that satisfactorily models the ideal passband is found by trial and error, by plotting the fft of each filter kernel trial with different orders and comparing it with the requested bandpass.
% From frequency response, it's clear the bird whistle is around 1700 to
% 2600 Hz. Define this
frange = [1700 2600];
order = round( 10*fs/frange(1) );
%fir1 takes in order and bandpass frequency limits. fir1 is used to reduce
%oscillation in the transition region, at the cost of reduced accuracy in
%this region.
%The frange input to fir1 has to be a fraction of the Nyquist frequency
filtkern = fir1(order,frange/(fs/2));
%Check filter kernel
figure
plot(filtkern,'linew',1)
xlabel('Time points')
title('Filter kernel (fir1)')
% And check filter fft; make sure it is similar to the bandpass requirement
% compute the power spectrum of the filter kernel
filtpow = abs(fft(filtkern)).^2;
% compute the frequencies vector and remove negative frequencies
hz = linspace(0,fs/2,floor(length(filtkern)/2)+1);
filtpow = filtpow(1:length(hz));
% Plot amplitude spectrum of the filter kernel
figure
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ylabel('Amplitude')
plot(hz,filtpow,'ks-','linew',1,'markerfacecolor','w');hold on
plot([0 frange(1) frange frange(2) fs/2],[0 0 1 1 0 0],'ro-','linew',1,'markerfacecolor','w')
legend({'Ideal bandpass','Designed bandpass'}')
title('Requested bandpass vs. Final designed bandpass')
% The amplitude spectrum of kernel above is satisfactory; use this to filter signal
fori = filter(filtkern,1,ori_signal);
% Compare original and filtered signal
figure
time=linspace(0,10,n);
plot(time,ori_signal);hold on
xlabel('Time (s)');
ylabel('Amplitude');
plot(time,fori)
legend({'Original Signal','Filtered Signal'})
xlim([5 5.1])
title('Time Signal zoomed in to 5 and 5.1 seconds')
hold off
%Compare PSD of original signal and filtered signal
Pref = 2*10^-5;
figure
% compute the power spectrum of the filter kernel
filtpow_ori = abs(fft(fori)/n).^2;
% compute the frequencies vector and remove negative frequencies
hz = linspace(0,fs/2,floor(n/2)+1);
filtpow_ori = filtpow_ori(1:length(hz));
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpow_ori/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(ori_signal_freqresp/Pref^2));
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)');
ylabel('Magnitude (dB)');
xlim([0 20000]);
ylim([-150 50]);
xline(1700);
xline(2600);
title('Frequency responses')
hold off
legend({'Original signal','FIR filtered'})

7. Apply zero-phase filter

Now, a point in time T the filtered signal is a weighted combination of the original signal in time 0 until T-1 convolved with the filter kernel. This gives a not totally accurate result, which results in a phase shift (i.e. the filtered signal is delayed compared to the original signal) and a reduced effectiveness in filtering signals outside the bandpass region. Since we are doing an offline signal analysis and thus know the original signal at time T+1 (i.e. we know the future), we can instead use the signals from the end of the signal up to T+1 to create the filtered signal at time T. This will be more accurate since the filtered signal is a function of what is already known, instead of being predicted from the past. This procedure is shown below.
The aforementioned phase shift is not immediately observable in the time plot above, but it is there.
% Reverse the original signal
sigR = ori_signal(end:-1:1);
% Then filter this reversed signal
fsig = filter(filtkern,1,sigR);
% Now reverse this signal
fsig = fsig(end:-1:1);
% And then plot to check
figure
plot(time,ori_signal,'linew',1)
hold on
plot(time,fori,'linew',1)
hold on
plot(time,fsig,'linew',1)
legend({'Original Signal','No Zero Phase Filter','With Zero Phase Filter'})
hold off
xlabel('Time (s)')
ylabel('Amplitude')
title('Time Signal zoomed in to 5 and 5.1 seconds')
xlim([5 5.1])
% Also plot PSD
Pref = 2*10^-5;
figure
filtpow = abs(fft(fsig)/n).^2;
hz = linspace(0,fs/2,floor(n/2)+1);
filtpow = filtpow(1:length(hz));
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpow_ori/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpow/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(ori_signal_freqresp/Pref^2));hold off
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)');
ylabel('Magnitude (dB)');
xlim([0 20000]);
title('Frequency responses')
ylim([-150 50]);
xline(1700);xline(2600);
legend({'Without zero-phase filter','With zero phase filter','Original signal'})
As seen here, there is better suppression of frequencies outside of the bandpass region, with a phase shift in the time domain signal being removed.

8. Edge effect and Using Reflection

At the start there is edge effect; the first few seconds of the filtered signal are not filtered correctly because for these datapoints, the original signal length is still smaller than the kernel; therefore the kernel uses wrong datapoints to create these first few filtered datapoints. This will generate signal components consisting of frequencies outside of the bandpass, thus limiting the filtering power.
To fix this, I add a reflection technique, where the original signal is extended back and forward using the reflection of the signal, filter this "extended" signal, filter the reverse of the result, reverse the result again, and then take only the relevant part of the signal. This ensures that all filtered datapoints are composed of a "complete" convolution between relevant parts of the original time signal and the filter kernel.
% First, add reflections to the original signal
fsigR = [ori_signal(end:-1:1); ori_signal; ori_signal(end:-1:1)];
% Then filter it
fsigR = filter(filtkern,1,fsigR);
% Now the zero-phase operation; reverse the signal
fsigR=fsigR(end:-1:1);
% Then filter this reversed signal
fsigR = filter(filtkern,1,fsigR);
% Reverse again to get correct signal
fsigR=fsigR(end:-1:1);
% Then only take the relevant parts of this final signal
fsigR = fsigR(n+1:end-n);
% Plot frequency response to make sure signal is actually improved
figure
% compute the power spectrum of the filter kernel
filtpowR = abs(fft(fsigR)/n).^2;
% compute the frequencies vector and remove negative frequencies
hz = linspace(0,fs/2,floor(n/2)+1);
filtpowR = filtpowR(1:length(hz));
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpow_ori/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpow/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(filtpowR/Pref^2));hold on
plot(hz,10*log10(ori_signal_freqresp/Pref^2));
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ylabel('Magnitude (dB)')
xlim([0 20000]);
ylim([-150 50]);
title('Frequency responses')
xline(1700);xline(2600);
legend({'Only FIR filter','FIR + Zero-phase filter','FIR + Zero-phase filter and reflection','Original Signal'}')
We observe from the frequency response plot that there is improvement in frequencies suppression below the passband and an improvement in suppression just outside the passband. In addition, the higher frequencies' suppression are more consistent. Therefore this filter is chosen as the final design.
